    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 25 with a clear offensive ceiling anchored by **Pete Crow-Armstrong**, who earns our daily high score of 78.91. His matchup against Sasaki is the most favorable on the slate; the pitcher\u2019s 5.52 xERA combined with a significant platoon advantage gives **Pete Crow-Armstrong** elite scoring potential, despite the suboptimal 8th-spot order placement. Similarly, **Junior Caminero** (73.53) remains a \"Strong\" start, capitalizing on a favorable matchup against Ober to anchor our utility spot. We also expect strong production from **Trea Turner** (68.86) and **Kyle Schwarber** (65.76); both benefit from the platoon edge against Elder and prime lineup positioning, ensuring they remain staples of our daily production model.\n\nOur most difficult bench decision involved **Victor Scott II**, whose 39.50 efficiency score fell just shy of our 40.0 floor. While we prioritize speed in this 5x5 format, the combination of a tough matchup against Woo (3.30 xERA) and an unfavorable 9th-order slot dragged his projection down sufficiently to keep him on the bench. Elsewhere, we are navigating health hurdles, as **Christian Yelich** and **Lars Nootbaar** remain sidelined, while **Zac Veen** continues his stint with Albuquerque. With the bottom of the order occupied by **Hyeseong Kim** and **Chase Meidroth**, we are closely monitoring the matchup volatility of **Dillon Dingler**\u2014his 43.97 score is buoyed by park factors but suppressed by a difficult platoon split against Singer, making him our most volatile starter today. We will continue to evaluate the depth provided by **Gary Sanchez**, **Luke Raley**, **Josh Smith**, **Jerar Encarnacion**, **Carson Benge**, and **Luis Pena** as we look to maximize daily efficiency and preserve our game caps.",
